comments.body: Thanks @trevorsless! Are these generally difficult to ID at the species level? Also, can you tell me if this one clinging to the branch because it's sleeping, or for some other reason? It seems like not the safest spot to rest, so the behavior was curious to me.

Yes, they're usually very difficult to identify from pictures alone.  My best guess here would be Nomada imbricata, but I'm far from confident.  They can often be found sleeping outside like this, since they're cuckoo bees that don't make any nests of their own.
Thanks for the info! Doesn't sleeping out in the open like this make them an easy target for birds or other predators? Or do they just not have many predators?
Potentially I suppose, but I'm not sure how significant of a concern predation is for them.

identifications.body: Maybe a wool carder bee, but I'm not sure.

description:
A turkey vulture visited my balcony several times today. Definitely my coolest animal encounter of the year so far!

This was shot from behind a window with UV-blocking film, which is slightly reflective (and why some of the photos are a bit hazy). The bird seemed to be interested in its reflection.

Multiple times it perched on the railing with its wings outstretched for awhile. Is this done for sunbathing, or something else?

description:
The same mites as in https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/60245515 , but this time at 100x and 400x magnification. 

The last two photos show damage done to a Rhipsalis baccifera (Mistletoe Cactus). They seem to prefer that over most of the other neighboring plants. They look like red spider mites, but there are no webs on any of the affected plants.
